class.description:
A web page that asks for [User] credentials and logs them in by setting cookies.
Rendering can be customized by creating the following method:
[code]func _render_user_page(request : WebServerRequest, d : Dictionary) -> void:[/code]
The [code]d[/code] [Dictionary] will contain the following data on a successful login:
[code]d["type"] = "render_login_success";
d["user"] = user;[/code]
The [code]d[/code] [Dictionary] will contain the following data normally, or on a failed login attempt:
[code]d["type"] = "render_login_request_default";
d["error_str"] = error_str; String, html containing the problems.
d["uname_val"] = uname_val; The username input value.
d["pass_val"] = pass_val; The password input value.[/code]
If you want to reimplement this class yourself, this is how to set up a user's session on login success:
[code]//PScript:
HTTPSession session = request.get_or_create_session();
session.add("user_id", user.get_user_id());
WebServerCookie c = WebServerCookie.new();
c.set_data("session_id", session.get_session_id());
c.set_path("/");
request.response_add_cookie(c);
// ...
// Send the request[/code]
Note that two factor authentication is not supported by this class, as it needs project wide components and component communication (sending emails, TOTP, etc.). If you need 2FA, reimplementing this class is recommended (the logic is only ~50 lines of code), and then 2FA can be added on top of it. See the [SMTPClient] and [TOTP] classes. Also, there is a qr code + totp demo in the docs repository.
